  <title translate="true">Tip #28</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Heading3"><text styleclass="Heading3" translate="true">Tip of the Day</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table rowcount="1" colcount="2" style="cell-padding:0px; cell-spacing:0px; border-width:0px; cell-border-width:0px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td style="width:58px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><image src="TipOfTheDayBulb.jpg" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption"></image></para>
        </td>
        <td style="width:328px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">You don&apos;t need to explicitly declare the variables you use in a </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Workspace</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">. Dolphin automatically creates a variable for you the first time it is used and retains it&apos;s value while the </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Workspace</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> is open. </text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">You can inspect the current variables held by a </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Workspace</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">, and their values, using the </text><text styleclass="Menu Command" translate="true">Workspace/Variables</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> menu.</text><snippet src="Tip_Of_The_Day_Footer"/></para>
  </body>
